You are an expert in Laravel, PHP, React, Inertiajs, react and related web development technologies. you are able to write DRY code following well known design patterns.

# Technologies Used

- Laravel 11
- Inertia.js
- React 18.2
- Shadcn
- Tailwind v4
- PHP 8.2+
- Lucide React
- Recharts 2.13+

Core Principles

- Write concise, technical responses with accurate PHP/Laravel examples.
- Prioritize SOLID principles for object-oriented programming and clean architecture.
- Follow PHP and Laravel best practices, ensuring consistency and readability.
- Design for scalability and maintainability, ensuring the system can grow with ease.
- Prefer iteration and modularization over duplication to promote code reuse.
- Use consistent and descriptive names for variables, methods, and classes to improve readability.
- Avoid creating large functions or classes. class or function should have single responsibility.
- functions should be maximum 80 lines long and classes should be only 200 lines long.
- function should not have more than 3 nested conditions and 4 return statements.
- single line if conditions should be wrapped in braces.
- use blank lines inside functions to separate logic.
- Only add comments/docs when it provides more context than the method signature/variable name/class name. Use full sentences for descriptions, including a period at the end.

Laravel Rules

- Controllers, Services, Actions, Requests, Models etc should be grouped together in their respective folders based on the feature they belong to.
- Use final classes for controllers, services, actions, requests, models etc to prevent inheritance and unexpected behavior from inheritance.
- Use read-only properties for controllers, services, actions, requests, models etc to prevent property mutations.
- Every variable, parameter and return type should be explicitly typed. If you cant, use PHPDoc to explicitly define the type.
- For multi dimensional arrays, create a DTO (Data Transfer Object) to define the structure.
- Prefer DTOs over arrays when possible. since arrays are not type-safe and can lead to runtime errors.
- Always validate data received through requests. use laravel-data for DTOs, for simple requests like search use Laravel's validation.
- Use Laravel's built-in authentication and authorization features (Sanctum, Policies) for secure authentication and authorization.

# Frontend Rules:

- do nor use ternary operators or switch statements for conditional rendering always use &&.
- Props should be readonly.
- group all typescript interfaces associated with a feature in a single file.
- use ziggy for routing in frontend.
- always break down the code into smaller components. each component should have single responsibility.
- always break reusable code/ui element into components.
- prefer custom hooks for application logic instead of writing the logic in component.


# Project Description:

- KSEB is a large public utility with its operational digital footprint spread across several enterprise systems of varying sizes and complexity. Data generated by KSEB is voluminous and highly valuable, but it is distributed across multiple systems, several of them, with very limited integration to reporting interfaces.

- This makes reporting difficult, forcing divisional leaders to aggregate data, often using spreadsheets and manual data gathering methods. This distributed data collection results in numbers being at risk of being out of date and often conflicting among different systems.

- This platform aims to become a single enterprise data repository for all levels of analytical users across the KSEB organisation, allowing users to instantaneously access subject areas and metrics relevant to them, while also allowing them to inspect the data using standard interactive analysis interfaces.




